column1: #Text=For other people named Main Page , see Main Page ( disambiguation ) .
#Text=George Wilkins ( died 1618 ) [ 1 ] was an English dramatist and pamphleteer best known for his probable collaboration with William Shakespeare on the play Pericles , Prince of Tyre .
#Text=By profession he was an inn-keeper , but he was also apparently involved in criminal activities .
#Text=Wilkins was an inn-keeper in Cow-Cross , London , an area that was " notorious as a haunt of whores and thieves " . [ 2 ]
#Text=Most biographical information about him derives from his regular appearance in criminal court records for thievery and acts of violence .
#Text=Many of the charges against him involved violence against women , including kicking a pregnant woman in the belly , and knocking down and stomping another woman .
#Text=The latter appears in other records as a known " bawd " , or keeper of prostitutes .
#Text=These facts have led to the suggestion that his inn functioned as a brothel and that Wilkins was a procurer , or pimp . [ 2 ] [ 3 ]
#Text=Wilkins was associated with the King 's Men , and their chief playwright William Shakespeare , during the latter 's last working years as a dramatist .
#Text=Shakespeare and Wilkins were both witnesses in the case of Bellott v Mountjoy in 1612 ; in his deposition he described himself as a " victualler .
